POV: It's one in the morning and you're my neighbor, waking up to go to the bathroom. You come back into your bedroom and catch movement out of the corner of your eye. As you draw closer to the window, you can see a kitchen light on in the opposite house across the yard. There you see a girl who looks far too awake for one AM. A package of Oreos and a glass of milk are lying completely forgotten on the counter as the girl sways and spins and bounces in the most ridiculous lack of dancing skill you have ever seen in your life. She has headphones in, and seems to be lip-syncing so as not to wake up the rest of the house. As you watch, the song appears to be light and magical (considering the breezy twirls and blithe smile on the girl's face). But then something shifts. Conflict enters the girl's face. She spins violently to the point where you genuinely fear she'll slip and crash behind the counter. She now appears to be screaming. She throws her arms above her head and thrashes in a psychotic frenzy. She fists the air in front of her and silently shrieks into the sky. She spins faster and faster and faster as she withers slowly out of sight behind the counter without a sound.... And then you realize...she's jamming to Owl City's brand-new album, and she's probably listening to The Tornado....

7:51 AM
Like, Adam made the perfect album, something in a totally different league than his old work
7:53 AM
I can’t compare Coco Moon to, say, ATBAB cause I think they were written under fundamentally different circumstances. ATBAB was kinda the height of his career, and he was still a dreamer trying to find his place in the world. Coco Moon is him having found it, and now that he is using the skills he learned along the way to tell the kinds of stories he has always dreamed of and the lessons he has learned on the way to where he is now (edited)
